(A) release acetylcholine;
Atropine competitively antagonizes acetylcholine at muscarinic receptors. It does not release acetylcholine.

(B) reactivate cholinesterase;
Atropine does not reactivate cholinesterase. Organophosphates inhibit cholinesterase. Pralidoxime can be used to reactivate cholinesterase.

(C) relieve the noradrenergic toxicity;
Atropine's primary mechanism of action is at muscarinic receptors, not noradrenergic receptors. Therefore, it does not relieve noradrenergic toxicity.

(D) reverse the neuromuscular paralysis;
Atropine can reverse the muscarinic effects of organophosphates, but it does not reverse neuromuscular paralysis. Neuromuscular paralysis caused by organophosphates is due to the accumulation of acetylcholine at nicotinic receptors.

(E) relieve the muscarinic symptoms;
Atropine relieves muscarinic symptoms by blocking the action of acetylcholine at muscarinic receptors. This is the primary mechanism by which atropine is beneficial in organophosphate poisoning.
